headline: President Trump celebrates after Senate impeachment trial acquittal

utterances.speaker: NEIL CAVUTO, FOX NEWS ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Some would even argue we've never seen it before. "The Five" starts right now.

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I am Dana Perino, along with Emily Compagno, Juan Williams, Lawrence Jones, and Greg Gutfeld. It is 5:00 in New York City, and this is THE FIVE. President Trump has been acquitted, but the fight over impeachment appears far from over, a triumphant Trump taking a major victory lap at the National Prayer Breakfast this morning, holding up an acquitted newspaper headline and attacking his political foes.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES
utterances.sentences: I don't like people who use their faith as justification for doing what they know is wrong, nor do I like people who say I pray for you when they know that that's not so.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Nancy Pelosi responding with these harsh words.

utterances.speaker: REP. NANCY PELOSI (D-CA)
utterances.sentences: I pray hard for him because he is so off the track of our Constitution, our values, our country. He's talking about things that he knows little about, faith and prayer. He is impeached forever, no matter what he says or whatever headlines he wants to carry around.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Pelosi also taking direct aim at the president's state of the union speech, which she tore up.

utterances.speaker: PELOSI
utterances.sentences: To me, like -- a little fixated being last year, too. And what happened instead was the president using the Congress of the United States as a backdrop for a reality show. I tore up a manifesto of mistruths. And I don't need any lessons from anybody, especially a president of the United States, about dignity. Next year, we will have a new president of the United States. It's an absolute imperative for our country.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Then this afternoon, the president going off on impeachment, Pelosi, and much more.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: We were treated unbelievably unfairly. And you have to understand, we first went through Russia, Russia, Russia. It was all bull -- Adam Schiff is a vicious, horrible person. Nancy Pelosi is a horrible person. And she wanted to impeach a long time ago, and she said I pray for the president. I pray for the pre -- she didn't pray. She may pray but she prays for the opposite.   They brought me to the final stages of impeachment. But now, we have that gorgeous word. I never thought a word with sound so good. It's called total acquittal.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right, Emily, total acquittal. You heard it.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: This was funny because he said -- look, think what resonates with me so strongly here is the small world that Pelosi is living in that she truly doesn't see that this entire time what's resonated with this president and for the American people is the fact that the entire time he has aligned himself with them, with you, and me.  He's never badmouthed or criticized the public or an entire segment of the population, which is why the Democrats continue to shoot themselves in the foot and continue to seem so out of touch. And it's also why the American people took such offense at her ripping up that speech because it was ripping up them. It was ripping up names and policies and help and identification and a feeling of being heard that this president has done this entire time.  And, you know, we've sat through two years of Mueller and then six months of impeachment. And the Democrats have tried to sell the American people what they say that Trump did, what they said he did. And no one wants to go off that ledge anymore. We have been sold a bombshell over and over again. Who wants to take another leap of faith? Everyone is exhausted. And to see her perpetuating that same self-lie in that same echo chamber, there's nothing to show for it, except our fatigue, and the fact that she's not going to be speaker next time around.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Greg, the speaker is having what you would call a no-good, very bad week.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: Yes. I don't know if it can get any worse but it probably could. I have a piece advice for these people. If you want to get Trump out of the White House, here is an easy strategy. Wait five years, OK? That's all you have to do. I know people are all upset about the presser, but he deserves do -- I would've been worse. I mean, three years.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: There's no doubt. You would've been so --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I -- at least he thanked everybody. I would've just been screaming my head -- I would be using much, much worse language.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I thought the presser was hilarious. I thought it was great. He was right to say everything. But I'm aware that there will be people, like Juan, who disagree completely and people out there. So there is one side that feels really bad about this and one side that's ecstatic. So we can agree that the both sides are looking at the same thing and seeing two different things, right?   So what's the answer? Which side is best at predicting the outcomes? So when you have these two different visions, what predicted the implosion of collusion or the obstruction or Kavanaugh, impeachment? It's the people who were happy today, right? That side has been able to predict, with almost 100 percent certainty, what was going to happen. And the other side, which is so emotionally damaged, that's damaged because every time their side is wrong because of their cognitive dissonance, they cannot understand why the vision in their head isn't matching the reality outside. And so you have these people -- Nancy did not look like -- she looked like she had had it.  And I think for reasons that had nothing to do with Trump. But her own side has not helped her. Every time that they predict something, it's bad and it bleeds into Iowa. They get everything wrong, should learn something.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: January was like Iran, impeachment. Then they have Iowa. It is like the ides of February, Juan. What's going on? What do you think about the speaker's response today?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.sentences: I think she was right. I mean, look, I just couldn't believe what the president did in the East Room. I mean, obviously, we just played him using profanity. I just don't think it's me when I see a president behave like that. And, you know, I think this is inappropriate and wrong. I think most Americans, by the way, would agree with me. I don't think it's that he's in touch with Americans. I think he did a power play. And there were a lot of spineless Republicans in the Senate who just couldn't deal with a matter of conscience. And when it comes to religion, which was so central, by the way, in the way that Mitt Romney --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- hang on. Yes, what Romney did and what Nancy Pelosi did would say this is appalling behavior. And they, therefore, acted in accordance with their conscience and with their faith as what Mitt Romney said.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's inconvenient.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- in other words, and then the president speaks to this religion angle today, Dana. But, of course, he behaved inappropriately at the prayer breakfast. This guy --

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.sentences: -- when he said she was sedated.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- this guy doesn't know anything about religion. He doesn't know anything about forgiveness, about humility. No, he doesn't. He doesn't live his life that way. He says he doesn't forgive people. Greg, you said don't judge words, judge by actions. Look at his actions.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, and now he's acquitted. That's a great action.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: This guy does not live like Jesus. This is not a Christian life.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Let's get Lawrence.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: Here's the deal. For years, we've heard the Democrats say that Nancy Pelosi was the adult in the room. She doesn't do name-calling. She called the president sedated today. She's classy. She's about decorum. In the House, she ripped up his speech. And so the Democrats can no longer claim that they have the moral high ground. And what I've been telling people for years is that the way Trump behaves is much like many of the people that are in the House. Many of the other leaders, they just do it behind closed doors. The difference from Trump is, he is who he is, and this was a day of celebration because not only was it about him. They destroyed this man's family, went after everyone in the cabinet, went after every business associate. They used political pressure in the prosecution to squeeze people on false charges that had nothing to do with collusion. They destroyed everyone that was associated with the president. So, of course --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So he just gets away with lying?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, he just lies in the state of the union. He tells outright lies about healthcare. Oh, I am protecting people with pre-existing conditions.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Don't a say word.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: -- Democrats on pre-existing conditions. But again, you all didn't want to stand up for the kids, with school choice. You all didn't want to stand for the Tuskegee airmen.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: -- essentially more people being on food stamps.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know what I liked about that speech -- the state of the union, it was reality TV with a TV performance, but it was insulting to the House, because you don't give Rush Limbaugh a Medal of Freedom. The first lady put it. It was just like a sideshow.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: Democrats would think their strategy as the president is rising in approval rating or they're still going to take this and say you all trying to impeach him. You all tried for the Russian conspiracy. And it still didn't work. His approval rating is going up.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. We've got to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Believe me. Greg will take a look at some of the most the most over-the-top reactions to impeachment, not including the one you just saw.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The consequence of a delusion, the breakdown that follows after truth is revealed.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Slash his throat, every effen Republican. Slash Republicans' throats. Slash fascist throats, death to fascists.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That person is going to do well in life. Imagine being his parents. I would make a joke but I feel sorry for them. It's a break down. What you also see on social media where celebrities resort to, all caps, insanity in response to cheeky memes. Remember this one? Trump just reposted it, prompting Bette Midler to scream frantically.   You think this is a joke, don't you? It's not. He means it. He will change the rules. And his enablers will let him. If he wins again, he will rule until you until he dies. You die or both then you get Ivanka if you're lucky. Of course, that's a joke but maybe not. At least Ivanka is sane. Midler is so nutty. Elephants keep trying to eat her. Meanwhile, after Trump's presser, CNN goes full Freudian.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: This was a very disturbing tableau for the country. It was dark because he's made clear that his mind is dark. This is somebody in deep psychological distress right now, self-pity, insecure, angry.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That is a straight news reporter.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Once again, CNN's very best become psychiatrists, diagnosing mental illness. No surprise Harwood a paranoid narcoleptic who eats his own hair. I'm kidding. But see, anyone can play doctor, especially in times of hysteria when you see someone else's good time is your bad. Emotion fuels the anger. The media gins it up for ratings, making the hangover worse once the fantasy collapses.  It happened before, righteous rage followed by depression. And it'll happen again. But remember, the media and the Dems resorted to similar attacks on Reagan, Bush, McCain, Bourque (ph), and yes even poor Mitt, the dog abuser. But the attacks on Trump are more plentiful and more intense. Why is that, because he fought back? Remember when people mocked Trump defenders who would say but he fights. Hell, they were right. It's why he's winning and why the other side keeps screaming. Dana, I have a theory that you should only tweet in all caps if your house is on fire, and then you shouldn't even be on Twitter.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes. Like, for people that are on Twitter a lot, they think that they're having an impact, but it really is, like, they are just talking to themselves. It's like spitting in the wind.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And it goes away so quickly so it's kind of pointless.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's rude, spitting in the wind, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, if you spit in the wind, sometimes it comes back and hits you in the face.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Exactly. It's an apt analogy for the Democrats.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The other thing -- like Bernie fights.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Bernie fights, exactly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: He's not going to take these Iowa results lying down.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I take a lot of things lying down, Lawrence, because I'm lazy. Let me ask you this. Did you see that -- what did you think of that video of that kid? Isn't that the creepiest thing? I thought it was funny, and I they look at it. I go there's -- what is wrong with these people in college?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: Well, I covered college for two years on campus reform, and this is typical behavior. These people -- and it is part of the professors' fall as well, because, you know, we think the other side just have -- I think Juan has bad ideas but I love Juan. We go. We have a drink and everything. They're being talked -- that the other side on college campuses are evil.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: That they're a threat to Democracy, that they're a threat to the country. And when you have these developing minds that should be learning both sides of the political spectrum, and you put that nonsense in their head, they just start reacting like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know, Juan --

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: -- we don't know.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. I heard that that kid, Juan, is actually now getting a job at CNN as a media reporter.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Could be, or maybe he'll replace you, I don't know. It seems to me, though, that -- I mean it's crazy to extrapolate from -- that's just bad behavior, and clearly threatening. I would -- if the police are aware of it, they should be checking him out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Drugs maybe an issue. But you can't extrapolate and say that's typical behavior on college campuses.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: If you took an example of a right-winger saying something crazy and said all Republicans are all conservatives, we would say no, that's not fair.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- a trend, Juan. I have three examples.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. So to me, the big news here it seems to me, look, trump and people who are upset, and I think lots of Democrats are upset at the idea that there was a power play that was devoid of paying attention to what was going on that you had Republicans who say he did something wrong, but we don't want to impeach him. It's like people just are lacking in saying conviction and holding to the promise to uphold the Constitution.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All right. It's over, Juan. We've got to move on to the next step in this, which is the next impeachment. Emily, the thing that drives me crazy is the diagnosis, when people diagnose people's problems. I mean, doctors aren't allowed to do that without seeing a patient. But Harwood is?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I agree. Also, that video of that guy is that's my entire metaphor for the Democratic Party right now, which is that the Democratic Party leadership are screaming in the middle of their echo chamber. They are fueled entirely by emotion and contempt. And that's one of the Four Horsemen, right? Remember this. John Gottman saying once you have contempt, like, the whole world is over. There's no -- you can't proceed with logic anymore. And meanwhile, while this guy is, like, literally going crazy, screaming at what he thinks is so true. All around him is everyone -- I've got to get to class in about 20 minutes. I'm videotaping this insane guy. Like, what am I having for dinner? I've got to do this. Because meanwhile, we have these statistics that came that was covered in the state of the union. I mean, the DOW has been up almost 60 percent since the election, S&P almost 56 percent, 90 percent of Americans are satisfied with their personal life. These are things that matter. So literally, the rest of the party watching the leadership in the middle go beside themselves and make no production whatsoever. And at the end of the day, we are going to learn at the ballot box who made the most sense to them. It's not Pelosi.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. Well, let me just tell you. It's like -- what is it, 80 percent of Americans are represented by the senators who voted to convict and remove this president.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, you know, it didn't work out. Coming up, bitter Democrats claim Trump wasn't really acquitted, plus, the media's new love affair with Mr. Mitt Romney.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The post impeachment political battle rages on, and some Democrats say President Trump was not truly acquitted. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: This vote is no vindication. It's no real acquittal. It's no victory.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: am uncomfortable with the word acquitted because that implies that there was a full and fair trial.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Well, but there's no vindication from a rigged trial.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's a giant asterisk next to the president's acquittal. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And Senator Mitt Romney, he's being praised for voting to convict President Trump on the abuse of power article of impeachment.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: God bless him for his courage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It will cement Senator Romney's legacy.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I do want to salute Mitt Romney.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: This was a profile in courage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I was listening to a decent and honorable man who stood up and did the right thing.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: He is now the president of the Republican resistance to Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: It was something that I've never actually seen since I've been in the Senate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I guess they are saying that he voted as an act of conscience, Lawrence, and that, you know, it's a fact he was the one who stood up. I think I read today that in all the prior impeachments, the president who was being impeached was able to hold his party in line. So this is the first historically. But I think lots of Republicans saying, oh, it's just Democrats celebrating Romney. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: Well, it's clear, because he was the devil before, you know -- all this nonsense. You only have courage when you stand with the Democrats. That's apparently they have defined it as. Courage is when you decide to vote against the president. Look, on a sad note, though, this is bad for the Democrats. It is bitterness, and they can't move forward. The game is over. He has been acquitted. That's it. You move on. You try to beat him in the next election. Instead, because they have no message, the party is in disarray. They don't know how to control the progressive wing. And I think this is not going to even be a competition when it comes to November. It won't be a competition, because they have no message.  They have no leadership right now, can't even run Iowa, right? But they are still worried about the president, impeachment, and so forth.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: By the way, Dana, did you think that -- I saw that Mitt Romney did several interviews before he actually voted. Do you think he was trying to defend his legacy? How do you interpret what happened here?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, I asked Mike Lee today who's on the daily briefing if -- because he is the other senator from Utah, if he had talked to Mr. Romney before, and the answer was no. But they -- I think he knew that the blowback was coming. He knew that he was going to be called a traitor. He knew people that people were going to mock his religion and say that he's just a faker. So I think he knew all of that. So he is savvy enough to know, like, he lost the presidential election when Obama was up for re-election. And so he knew what the media attacks were going to be. But a couple of things, on the Democrats saying that he's not acquitted, do they now think that the media is fake news, because all of the headline say acquittal. So it is acquittal. And I think that the spin that it's not really acquittal, that might work in some fundraising but it's not going to work at the ballot box for sure. Plus, don't forget it was Harry Reid, the senator -- when he was the majority leader, who suggested that Mitt Romney never paid taxes. And all these people who are praising Mitt Romney now did nothing to stand up and say that was wrong. And even when Harry Reid later on was like I was just lying, but that's cool, right? All of them are, like, that's fine. You can do that to people and that's fine. Mitt Romney knows he's going to be lonely. And he will be eating alone at the lunch table. And I think he's accepted that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It's funny. I remember that when Mitt Romney was nominated, you had Republicans speak so highly of him as a man of family, a man of faith, for example.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes, of course.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And then in the last week, I've seen Republicans, conservatives just absolutely skewer him alive, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Are you telling me that politics is a team sport thing that you end up supporting the person that is leaving the party?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, but I'm saying that Republicans are now attacking and libeling Romney who once praised him --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know I don't have a problem. Mitt can do whatever he wants. And I think the Democrats need him. It's like, you know, how people have therapy animals after a really traumatic event. You know, is their therapy weasel. And they are clinging to him. At least we have Mitt, it's OK. You can have Mitt. I don't care. But I don't need anybody to lecture me on lack of character or a lack of conscience as though he's somehow the epitome of that. Please, don't do that to me. I don't need that. Here's the deal. We have two different men, Mitt and Trump, they're vastly different. The Dems would have preferred to have Mitt because he doesn't fight, all right, but Trump does. So this is how the argument is always going to be. Mitt, he is the nice guy who loses. Trump's the animal who wins. And that upsets people. I don't care. I really don't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I remember you did care when Trump insulted John McCain.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And I have been through this. And I wrote a book on it. And I said that once he got elected and he became my president, I'd give him a chance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You gave him a pass or a chance?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Did you hear me?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think you might just given him a pass.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what? You're screwed up in the brain, Juan. I said chance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: When you said you give them a chance --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Look at his deeds and not his words. I said this so many times --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Do you sleep at this table?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I'm saying, well, his deeds don't seem to support the idea that, oh yes, he's doing great.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Look at the economy. Look at peace, look at prosperity.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh my God, Juan. Yes, those are called deeds.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Look at --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: If you want to get mad about his words, you've been doing it for three years.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, I'm saying, look at his deeds. I think --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It gets you nowhere.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Has he delivered on the wall? Wait, has he delivered on wall? Has he done something about healthcare?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, so far the wall is coming.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Our troops -- are we sending more troops to the Middle East? All right, so Emily.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: So on Mitt, what's interesting is that you know, when he ran for president, those ads, the DNC ads, you guys remember those? Like Paul Ryan pushing the grandma off a cliff and big bird, and he was absolutely vilified. So it's a little difficult to take with any credibility or honesty. These people who are now championing him were the same people that say, Look, you're innocent until proven guilty. I thought Senator Scott had an incredible comment today, which is that look, you know, we thought through 60 hours of testimony and 190 video clips and 13 witnesses, and look, if you started out with the presumption of innocence, then 100 percent there was an acquittal. But if you started out with a presumption and a self-conviction of guilt, then no wonder that you came to that guilt conclusion. And really quickly on Hunter, because I think this is important and will probably be circling back to this. The Treasury Department has complied -- has complied with the Republican senators request for that the highly sensitive financial documents, right, for Hunter and his associates. And we have now a leading Democrat on the committee who's saying, we'll, the origins of the evidence are highly questionable. And I just have to throw out there that, you know, the entire FISA court, the entire surveillance warrants, everything was based on evidence of questionable origin and no one cared about it back then. So I find it curious that automatically and already Democrats on the Hill are carrying about questionable origin of evidence when it comes to Hunter Biden.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right, if you thought what's going on with the Iowa caucuses is bad, wait until you hear what just happened. It's unbelievable, but it's next for you on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: The DNC has said enough is enough with the disaster, that is the Iowa caucuses. Chairman Tom Perez is calling for an immediate re-candidacy. Even though we don't know who the -- who won the caucus yet, Bernie Sanders is declaring victory over Mayor Pete. And after his embarrassing showing in the Hawkeye State, Joe Biden is getting in the gutter to attack the new front runners.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN (D), PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: But if Senator Sanders is a nominee for the party, every Democrat in America up and down the ballot, blue states, red states, purple states will have to carry the label Senator Sanders has chosen for himself, Democratic Socialist. It's a risk, to be just straight up with you, for this party to nominate someone who's never held an office higher than mayor of a town of 100,000 people in Indiana.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.sentences: But Bernie and Mayor Pete are fighting back against Biden's attacks.

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (D-VT), PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: Let me tell my good friend, Joe, that when we're dealing with somebody like Donald Trump, he will pin any label that he wants on any candidate.

And it's also why the American people took such offense at her ripping up that speech because it was ripping up them. It was ripping up names and policies and help and identification and a feeling of being heard that this president has done this entire time. And, you know, we've sat through two years of Mueller and then six months of impeachment. And the Democrats have tried to sell the American people what they say that Trump did, what they said he did. And no one wants to go off that ledge anymore. We have been sold a bombshell over and over again. Who wants to take another leap of faith? Everyone is exhausted. And to see her perpetuating that same self-lie in that same echo chamber, there's nothing to show for it, except our fatigue, and the fact that she's not going to be speaker next time around.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg, the speaker is having what you would call a no-good, very bad week.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.utterance: Yes. I don't know if it can get any worse but it probably could. I have a piece advice for these people. If you want to get Trump out of the White House, here is an easy strategy. Wait five years, OK? That's all you have to do. I know people are all upset about the presser, but he deserves do -- I would've been worse. I mean, three years.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: There's no doubt. You would've been so --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I -- at least he thanked everybody. I would've just been screaming my head -- I would be using much, much worse language.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I thought the presser was hilarious. I thought it was great. He was right to say everything. But I'm aware that there will be people, like Juan, who disagree completely and people out there. So there is one side that feels really bad about this and one side that's ecstatic. So we can agree that the both sides are looking at the same thing and seeing two different things, right? So what's the answer? Which side is best at predicting the outcomes? So when you have these two different visions, what predicted the implosion of collusion or the obstruction or Kavanaugh, impeachment? It's the people who were happy today, right? That side has been able to predict, with almost 100 percent certainty, what was going to happen. And the other side, which is so emotionally damaged, that's damaged because every time their side is wrong because of their cognitive dissonance, they cannot understand why the vision in their head isn't matching the reality outside. And so you have these people -- Nancy did not look like -- she looked like she had had it. And I think for reasons that had nothing to do with Trump. But her own side has not helped her. Every time that they predict something, it's bad and it bleeds into Iowa. They get everything wrong, should learn something.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: January was like Iran, impeachment. Then they have Iowa. It is like the ides of February, Juan. What's going on? What do you think about the speaker's response today?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, FOX NEWS HOST
utterances.utterance: I think she was right. I mean, look, I just couldn't believe what the president did in the East Room. I mean, obviously, we just played him using profanity. I just don't think it's me when I see a president behave like that. And, you know, I think this is inappropriate and wrong. I think most Americans, by the way, would agree with me. I don't think it's that he's in touch with Americans. I think he did a power play. And there were a lot of spineless Republicans in the Senate who just couldn't deal with a matter of conscience. And when it comes to religion, which was so central, by the way, in the way that Mitt Romney --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- hang on. Yes, what Romney did and what Nancy Pelosi did would say this is appalling behavior. And they, therefore, acted in accordance with their conscience and with their faith as what Mitt Romney said.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's inconvenient.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- in other words, and then the president speaks to this religion angle today, Dana. But, of course, he behaved inappropriately at the prayer breakfast. This guy --

utterances.speaker: LAWRENCE JONES, FOX NEWS CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.utterance: -- when he said she was sedated.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- this guy doesn't know anything about religion. He doesn't know anything about forgiveness, about humility. No, he doesn't. He doesn't live his life that way. He says he doesn't forgive people. Greg, you said don't judge words, judge by actions. Look at his actions.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, and now he's acquitted. That's a great action.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: This guy does not live like Jesus. This is not a Christian life.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. Let's get Lawrence.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Here's the deal. For years, we've heard the Democrats say that Nancy Pelosi was the adult in the room. She doesn't do name-calling. She called the president sedated today. She's classy. She's about decorum. In the House, she ripped up his speech. And so the Democrats can no longer claim that they have the moral high ground. And what I've been telling people for years is that the way Trump behaves is much like many of the people that are in the House. Many of the other leaders, they just do it behind closed doors. The difference from Trump is, he is who he is, and this was a day of celebration because not only was it about him. They destroyed this man's family, went after everyone in the cabinet, went after every business associate. They used political pressure in the prosecution to squeeze people on false charges that had nothing to do with collusion. They destroyed everyone that was associated with the president. So, of course --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So he just gets away with lying?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, he just lies in the state of the union. He tells outright lies about healthcare. Oh, I am protecting people with pre-existing conditions.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Don't a say word.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: -- Democrats on pre-existing conditions. But again, you all didn't want to stand up for the kids, with school choice. You all didn't want to stand for the Tuskegee airmen.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: -- essentially more people being on food stamps.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what I liked about that speech -- the state of the union, it was reality TV with a TV performance, but it was insulting to the House, because you don't give Rush Limbaugh a Medal of Freedom. The first lady put it. It was just like a sideshow.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Democrats would think their strategy as the president is rising in approval rating or they're still going to take this and say you all trying to impeach him. You all tried for the Russian conspiracy. And it still didn't work. His approval rating is going up.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. We've got to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Believe me. Greg will take a look at some of the most the most over-the-top reactions to impeachment, not including the one you just saw.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The consequence of a delusion, the breakdown that follows after truth is revealed.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Slash his throat, every effen Republican. Slash Republicans' throats. Slash fascist throats, death to fascists.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That person is going to do well in life. Imagine being his parents. I would make a joke but I feel sorry for them. It's a break down. What you also see on social media where celebrities resort to, all caps, insanity in response to cheeky memes. Remember this one? Trump just reposted it, prompting Bette Midler to scream frantically. You think this is a joke, don't you? It's not. He means it. He will change the rules. And his enablers will let him. If he wins again, he will rule until you until he dies. You die or both then you get Ivanka if you're lucky. Of course, that's a joke but maybe not. At least Ivanka is sane. Midler is so nutty. Elephants keep trying to eat her. Meanwhile, after Trump's presser, CNN goes full Freudian.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This was a very disturbing tableau for the country. It was dark because he's made clear that his mind is dark. This is somebody in deep psychological distress right now, self-pity, insecure, angry.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is a straight news reporter.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Once again, CNN's very best become psychiatrists, diagnosing mental illness. No surprise Harwood a paranoid narcoleptic who eats his own hair. I'm kidding. But see, anyone can play doctor, especially in times of hysteria when you see someone else's good time is your bad. Emotion fuels the anger. The media gins it up for ratings, making the hangover worse once the fantasy collapses. It happened before, righteous rage followed by depression. And it'll happen again. But remember, the media and the Dems resorted to similar attacks on Reagan, Bush, McCain, Bourque (ph), and yes even poor Mitt, the dog abuser. But the attacks on Trump are more plentiful and more intense. Why is that, because he fought back? Remember when people mocked Trump defenders who would say but he fights. Hell, they were right. It's why he's winning and why the other side keeps screaming. Dana, I have a theory that you should only tweet in all caps if your house is on fire, and then you shouldn't even be on Twitter.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. Like, for people that are on Twitter a lot, they think that they're having an impact, but it really is, like, they are just talking to themselves. It's like spitting in the wind.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And it goes away so quickly so it's kind of pointless.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's rude, spitting in the wind, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, if you spit in the wind, sometimes it comes back and hits you in the face.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Exactly. It's an apt analogy for the Democrats.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The other thing -- like Bernie fights.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Bernie fights, exactly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He's not going to take these Iowa results lying down.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I take a lot of things lying down, Lawrence, because I'm lazy. Let me ask you this. Did you see that -- what did you think of that video of that kid? Isn't that the creepiest thing? I thought it was funny, and I they look at it. I go there's -- what is wrong with these people in college?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Well, I covered college for two years on campus reform, and this is typical behavior. These people -- and it is part of the professors' fall as well, because, you know, we think the other side just have -- I think Juan has bad ideas but I love Juan. We go. We have a drink and everything. They're being talked -- that the other side on college campuses are evil.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: That they're a threat to Democracy, that they're a threat to the country. And when you have these developing minds that should be learning both sides of the political spectrum, and you put that nonsense in their head, they just start reacting like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, Juan --

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: -- we don't know.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. I heard that that kid, Juan, is actually now getting a job at CNN as a media reporter.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Could be, or maybe he'll replace you, I don't know. It seems to me, though, that -- I mean it's crazy to extrapolate from -- that's just bad behavior, and clearly threatening. I would -- if the police are aware of it, they should be checking him out.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Drugs maybe an issue. But you can't extrapolate and say that's typical behavior on college campuses.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: If you took an example of a right-winger saying something crazy and said all Republicans are all conservatives, we would say no, that's not fair.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- a trend, Juan. I have three examples.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. So to me, the big news here it seems to me, look, trump and people who are upset, and I think lots of Democrats are upset at the idea that there was a power play that was devoid of paying attention to what was going on that you had Republicans who say he did something wrong, but we don't want to impeach him. It's like people just are lacking in saying conviction and holding to the promise to uphold the Constitution.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right. It's over, Juan. We've got to move on to the next step in this, which is the next impeachment. Emily, the thing that drives me crazy is the diagnosis, when people diagnose people's problems. I mean, doctors aren't allowed to do that without seeing a patient. But Harwood is?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I agree. Also, that video of that guy is that's my entire metaphor for the Democratic Party right now, which is that the Democratic Party leadership are screaming in the middle of their echo chamber. They are fueled entirely by emotion and contempt. And that's one of the Four Horsemen, right? Remember this. John Gottman saying once you have contempt, like, the whole world is over. There's no -- you can't proceed with logic anymore. And meanwhile, while this guy is, like, literally going crazy, screaming at what he thinks is so true. All around him is everyone -- I've got to get to class in about 20 minutes. I'm videotaping this insane guy. Like, what am I having for dinner? I've got to do this. Because meanwhile, we have these statistics that came that was covered in the state of the union. I mean, the DOW has been up almost 60 percent since the election, S&P almost 56 percent, 90 percent of Americans are satisfied with their personal life. These are things that matter. So literally, the rest of the party watching the leadership in the middle go beside themselves and make no production whatsoever. And at the end of the day, we are going to learn at the ballot box who made the most sense to them. It's not Pelosi.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Well, let me just tell you. It's like -- what is it, 80 percent of Americans are represented by the senators who voted to convict and remove this president.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know, it didn't work out. Coming up, bitter Democrats claim Trump wasn't really acquitted, plus, the media's new love affair with Mr. Mitt Romney.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The post impeachment political battle rages on, and some Democrats say President Trump was not truly acquitted. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This vote is no vindication. It's no real acquittal. It's no victory.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: am uncomfortable with the word acquitted because that implies that there was a full and fair trial.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Well, but there's no vindication from a rigged trial.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's a giant asterisk next to the president's acquittal. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And Senator Mitt Romney, he's being praised for voting to convict President Trump on the abuse of power article of impeachment.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: God bless him for his courage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It will cement Senator Romney's legacy.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I do want to salute Mitt Romney.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This was a profile in courage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: I was listening to a decent and honorable man who stood up and did the right thing.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: He is now the president of the Republican resistance to Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: It was something that I've never actually seen since I've been in the Senate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I guess they are saying that he voted as an act of conscience, Lawrence, and that, you know, it's a fact he was the one who stood up. I think I read today that in all the prior impeachments, the president who was being impeached was able to hold his party in line. So this is the first historically. But I think lots of Republicans saying, oh, it's just Democrats celebrating Romney. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Well, it's clear, because he was the devil before, you know -- all this nonsense. You only have courage when you stand with the Democrats. That's apparently they have defined it as. Courage is when you decide to vote against the president. Look, on a sad note, though, this is bad for the Democrats. It is bitterness, and they can't move forward. The game is over. He has been acquitted. That's it. You move on. You try to beat him in the next election. Instead, because they have no message, the party is in disarray. They don't know how to control the progressive wing. And I think this is not going to even be a competition when it comes to November. It won't be a competition, because they have no message. They have no leadership right now, can't even run Iowa, right? But they are still worried about the president, impeachment, and so forth.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way, Dana, did you think that -- I saw that Mitt Romney did several interviews before he actually voted. Do you think he was trying to defend his legacy? How do you interpret what happened here?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I asked Mike Lee today who's on the daily briefing if -- because he is the other senator from Utah, if he had talked to Mr. Romney before, and the answer was no. But they -- I think he knew that the blowback was coming. He knew that he was going to be called a traitor. He knew people that people were going to mock his religion and say that he's just a faker. So I think he knew all of that. So he is savvy enough to know, like, he lost the presidential election when Obama was up for re-election. And so he knew what the media attacks were going to be. But a couple of things, on the Democrats saying that he's not acquitted, do they now think that the media is fake news, because all of the headline say acquittal. So it is acquittal. And I think that the spin that it's not really acquittal, that might work in some fundraising but it's not going to work at the ballot box for sure. Plus, don't forget it was Harry Reid, the senator -- when he was the majority leader, who suggested that Mitt Romney never paid taxes. And all these people who are praising Mitt Romney now did nothing to stand up and say that was wrong. And even when Harry Reid later on was like I was just lying, but that's cool, right? All of them are, like, that's fine. You can do that to people and that's fine. Mitt Romney knows he's going to be lonely. And he will be eating alone at the lunch table. And I think he's accepted that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It's funny. I remember that when Mitt Romney was nominated, you had Republicans speak so highly of him as a man of family, a man of faith, for example.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, of course.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And then in the last week, I've seen Republicans, conservatives just absolutely skewer him alive, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Are you telling me that politics is a team sport thing that you end up supporting the person that is leaving the party?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, but I'm saying that Republicans are now attacking and libeling Romney who once praised him --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know I don't have a problem. Mitt can do whatever he wants. And I think the Democrats need him. It's like, you know, how people have therapy animals after a really traumatic event. You know, is their therapy weasel. And they are clinging to him. At least we have Mitt, it's OK. You can have Mitt. I don't care. But I don't need anybody to lecture me on lack of character or a lack of conscience as though he's somehow the epitome of that. Please, don't do that to me. I don't need that. Here's the deal. We have two different men, Mitt and Trump, they're vastly different. The Dems would have preferred to have Mitt because he doesn't fight, all right, but Trump does. So this is how the argument is always going to be. Mitt, he is the nice guy who loses. Trump's the animal who wins. And that upsets people. I don't care. I really don't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I remember you did care when Trump insulted John McCain.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And I have been through this. And I wrote a book on it. And I said that once he got elected and he became my president, I'd give him a chance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You gave him a pass or a chance?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you hear me?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think you might just given him a pass.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what? You're screwed up in the brain, Juan. I said chance.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: When you said you give them a chance --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Look at his deeds and not his words. I said this so many times --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Do you sleep at this table?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I'm saying, well, his deeds don't seem to support the idea that, oh yes, he's doing great.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Look at the economy. Look at peace, look at prosperity.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh my God, Juan. Yes, those are called deeds.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Look at --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: If you want to get mad about his words, you've been doing it for three years.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I'm saying, look at his deeds. I think --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It gets you nowhere.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Has he delivered on the wall? Wait, has he delivered on wall? Has he done something about healthcare?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, so far the wall is coming.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Our troops -- are we sending more troops to the Middle East? All right, so Emily.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: So on Mitt, what's interesting is that you know, when he ran for president, those ads, the DNC ads, you guys remember those? Like Paul Ryan pushing the grandma off a cliff and big bird, and he was absolutely vilified. So it's a little difficult to take with any credibility or honesty. These people who are now championing him were the same people that say, Look, you're innocent until proven guilty. I thought Senator Scott had an incredible comment today, which is that look, you know, we thought through 60 hours of testimony and 190 video clips and 13 witnesses, and look, if you started out with the presumption of innocence, then 100 percent there was an acquittal. But if you started out with a presumption and a self-conviction of guilt, then no wonder that you came to that guilt conclusion. And really quickly on Hunter, because I think this is important and will probably be circling back to this. The Treasury Department has complied -- has complied with the Republican senators request for that the highly sensitive financial documents, right, for Hunter and his associates. And we have now a leading Democrat on the committee who's saying, we'll, the origins of the evidence are highly questionable. And I just have to throw out there that, you know, the entire FISA court, the entire surveillance warrants, everything was based on evidence of questionable origin and no one cared about it back then. So I find it curious that automatically and already Democrats on the Hill are carrying about questionable origin of evidence when it comes to Hunter Biden.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, if you thought what's going on with the Iowa caucuses is bad, wait until you hear what just happened. It's unbelievable, but it's next for you on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: The DNC has said enough is enough with the disaster, that is the Iowa caucuses. Chairman Tom Perez is calling for an immediate re-candidacy. Even though we don't know who the -- who won the caucus yet, Bernie Sanders is declaring victory over Mayor Pete. And after his embarrassing showing in the Hawkeye State, Joe Biden is getting in the gutter to attack the new front runners.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN (D), PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: But if Senator Sanders is a nominee for the party, every Democrat in America up and down the ballot, blue states, red states, purple states will have to carry the label Senator Sanders has chosen for himself, Democratic Socialist. It's a risk, to be just straight up with you, for this party to nominate someone who's never held an office higher than mayor of a town of 100,000 people in Indiana.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: But Bernie and Mayor Pete are fighting back against Biden's attacks.

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS (D-VT), PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Let me tell my good friend, Joe, that when we're dealing with somebody like Donald Trump, he will pin any label that he wants on any candidate.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG (D), PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: If that argument is about electability and the ability to win, we just had the first election of the 2020 process and I think that's my answer.

utterances.speaker: JONES
utterances.utterance: Wow. Dana, are you surprised that it took this long for them to actually fight?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You know, I've been waiting for it for a long time because if you remember the 2015, beginning of that Republican Primary, that was a fight from the beginning, and it does never ended, and then it ultimately ended in the victory of President Trump. For these guys, if Buttigieg is at 26.2 percent, Sanders at 26.1 percent, that is so close. And you can imagine that you might call for a recount, right? But I believe that Tom Perez, the head of the DNC, was trying to get ahead of the candidates. And he was calling for a recap and seeing -- which is a recount. That doesn't mean you have to go back and re caucus, it's just a recount because all the candidates are going to do it themselves. Remember, the candidates had all their people keeping track as well, so they know. That's why I think Bernie Sanders feels very confident saying that he won. But I've also heard there's a lot of irregularities that came in. There's how many, is it 1,600 counties, Juan, or something, precincts? Just -- it's a lot to redo. And the Democrats desperately need some clarity as to where the party wants to go. They did not get it out of Iowa, but they'll get it in about five days in New Hampshire.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean, you got to be careful here, because it's not Tom Perez's responsibility because it was done by the state party, not the national party. But I think that what you get here is Tom Perez is now trying to assert control. He's trying to say, listen, one of the problems we had that night was you had -- you know, Bret, Martha, and everybody else on the air and nothing being said, nothing explained. So you had like a vacuum, and then you had conspiracy theories, finger- pointing and Trump celebrating, and jumping oh, the Democrats can't do anything. So I think he wants to take control and say, this is what happened and we're going to put it out, we're going to get this straight. Now, just to those numbers that you see up on the screen, I'll say Sanders to me did very well. I think Buttigieg outperformed expectations by far, so he did very well. Biden, I think is struggling. And he didn't initially want to compete in Iowa, really didn't think that much about competing in New Hampshire because it's Bernie's home territory. But what it means now is that he is on edge with regard to not only to Nevada, but South Carolina, and fundraising. He's got to start performing. If he's supposed to be elected, he got to win.
